LOS ANGELES, California — As the United States approaches the midterm elections, some political scientists warn the country may be drifting toward what they describe as “competitive authoritarianism,” while others argue democratic institutions remain resilient.


Staffan I. Lindberg of Sweden’s V-Dem Institute said the U.S. has crossed into what he calls an “electoral autocracy,” where elections still occur but democratic norms erode. Harvard professor Steven Levitsky, co-author of How Democracies Die, similarly described the U.S. as experiencing a “mild form” of competitive authoritarianism, citing rhetoric targeting media organizations, proposals to expand executive power, and aggressive immigration enforcement actions.


Levitsky referenced recent administration disputes with media companies and comments about using U.S. cities as military training grounds as troubling signals.


Other scholars disagree. George Washington University law professor Jonathan Turley said the administration is responding to perceived institutional bias and that political conflict does not automatically equal authoritarianism. Kurt Weyland of the University of Texas argued that checks and balances have constrained executive overreach, pointing to court rulings and public backlash over immigration enforcement operations in Minnesota.


With debates intensifying over federal monitoring of elections and voter data requests, researchers say the November midterms may serve as a significant test of American democratic norms.

WASHINGTON, D.C. — Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer on Sunday vowed to block the Safeguard American Voter Eligibility (SAVE) Act, calling the Republican-backed proposal “Jim Crow 2.0” and warning it could disenfranchise more than 20 million Americans.


During an appearance on CNN’s “State of the Union,” Schumer criticized Homeland Security Secretary Kristi Noem’s recent remarks about ensuring “the right people” vote in upcoming elections. Schumer dismissed concerns about widespread voter fraud, saying election irregularities are rare and arguing that immigration enforcement officers should not be stationed near polling places.


The SAVE Act, which passed the House 218-213, would require voters to show photo identification at polling sites and provide documentary proof of U.S. citizenship to register. The bill also allows for federal monitoring of polling locations. Supporters cite polling, including an August 2025 Pew Research Center survey showing broad public backing for voter ID requirements.


Schumer and other Democrats argue the measure goes beyond standard ID laws and could affect married women whose identification documents do not match birth records, as well as lower-income voters lacking ready access to documentation.


The bill now faces an uncertain path in the Senate, where Democrats could use procedural tools such as a filibuster to block passage despite limited bipartisan support in the House.

external.description: 米国連邦取引委員会（FTC）は、アップルがアップル・ニュースアプリで保守的なコンテンツを検閲しているとの指摘に懸念を示した。 FTC委員長のアンドリュー・ファーガソンは、右派シンクタンクのメディア・リサーチ・センターが報告した、アップルが保守系メディアをトップ20記事から除外したとする報告書を引用し、同社の利用規約や消費者への表明に反する可能性を指摘した。 ファーガソンは「イデオロギー的理由での検閲は断固として非難する」と述べ、FTCはアップルに政治的立場を強制する権限はないが、利用規約や合理的期待と合致しない場合はFTC法に違反する可能性があると警告した。 連邦通信委員会（FCC）主席のブレンダン・カーも「アップルには保守的見解を抑制する権利はない」と支持した。 ファーガソンはアップルに対し、利用規約の包括的な見直しと、ニュースキュレーションが方針に沿わない場合は速やかに是正するよう求めた。 この書簡は、ドナルド・トランプ大統領が同センターの報告をトゥルース・ソーシャルで共有した翌日に発表された。 FTCは昨年、プラットフォームによる政治的検閲に関する調査を開始しており、ユーザーへの圧力や黙らせ行為が法違反になる可能性を検討している。 アップルはコメント要請に即座に回答していない。
